Feb 1 2009 	Good Value	After walking down Eddy Street, which has to be said was a pretty intimadating road, I was feeling a bit concerned that I had not listened to a friend's protests that the tenderlion was not the area to stay in San Fran. Overall however we were happy with the Phoenix, although I have to admit that I don't think it is as cool as it would like to be, or perhaps used to be. The rooms were huge, particularly for the price and the hotel was excellent value. They had the funky motel vibe down to a tee. The bambudda lounge, which I had heard great things about was not as fab as I would have hoped, and I was surprised that the music was quite R&amp;B (However we did visit on a Saturday night, which perhaps is the only night this type of music is played) The staff on reception were all really friendly particularly Luke and were the coolest thing about the hotel. Although some of the surrounding streets were not so desirable the phoenix was well placed for visiting all of the cities areas of interest such as the mission, castro, alamo square, as well as the more obvious city centre sites. If this hotel was not next to such a rough part of Eddy St it would have been perfect, but then I am sure it would have been twice the price!	
Jan 15 2009	Rock 	This Is without a doubt the greatest botique hotel in the country and I've been to them all. for the last 20 years I have been touring with bands and every time we go to San Francisco we stay at the Phoenix. I'd say I've stayed there 10 times. It's very chick and a great location (5 minutes from Market St., 5 minutes from mitchell brother :-) ) Grade A party palace!. I always look forward to a fews days at the Phoenix.	
Jan 10 2009 	Great value	My husband and I just got back from a night at the Phoenix. We were there for a party at the Bambuddha Lounge, a great night spot adjacent to the hotel. The decor is what you see in the pictures: a funky revitalization of a 50's style motel. Our room was basic but quite clean and comfortable. There was a faint odor of cigarette smoke, even though it was supposedly non-smoking -- but it was faint enough not to bother us (our friends were initially assigned a much smokier-smelling room, but they asked to be switched and were accommodated). The front-desk staff was generally attentive and polite -- especially the night clerk, Luke. We were mostly surprised by what a great deal it was. We paid $133 with our AAA discount, including on-site parking and continental breakfast. Usually when breakfast is included at places like this, you're lucky to get coffee and doughnuts. Although not lavish, this one still exceeded my expectations: laid out buffet-style by the pool, it included coffee, several types of milk (soy, skim, whole, and half-and-half), OJ, several types of pastries (muffins, croissants, danishes, raisin bread), bagels with cream cheese (you could toast them if you liked), and whole fruit.The only major downside is the neighborhood (the Tenderloin), which is down-and-out. Then again, since your car is parked right there with complete in-and-out access, you don't need to walk around. Although you should make an exception and head to Brenda's French Soul Food, around the corner, for what might be the most delicious brunch you'll ever have. Overall, I would recommend the Phoenix for the value-conscious who appreciate funky style.	
