Jul 31 2007 	Great for the price	If you've never been to San Francisco and you want opulence, you shouldn't stay at The Phoenix. The Tenderloin is one of the least savory neighborhoods in the city and the hotel itself is geared more towards mildly successful rock musicians, or people who like to consider themselves as such, or people who like to consort with the above.However! If you're looking for an offbeat, cheap, fun, clean hotel perfectly located for easy access to most of what SF has to offer (or at least to transportation that affords easy access), with fantastic service and great food options nearby, The Phoenix is your place. You won't find another hotel in San Francisco quite like it. A free parking space comes with the room, but you probably won't need your own transportation once you're here because the subway and bus are within a couple of blocks, and much of the action is walkable.The hotel itself has a lot of character with a charming courtyard and pool, palm trees, and the occasional quirky Polynesian touch. Rock 'n' Roll is there to stay, too, with music recommendations in the lobby and, when I was there, a rock band tour bus-looking vehicle in the parking lot and a Smashing Pumpkins van.Absolutely the only drawback of the hotel is that it is in the Tenderloin, which ceases to be as much of an issue once you've acclimated to the many &quot;charms&quot; of San Francisco.Recommended!	
